{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d98bd65c-08fb-4e04-b52f-11f28498808c","content":"## What Changed\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, **implicit span conversions** now fully participate in overload resolution. For an `int[]` receiver, the compiler resolves `array.Contains(num)` to:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<int>(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)   // ← NEW winner\n```\n\ninstead of the previous:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)           // ← old winner\n```\n\n`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct** — it cannot be represented in expression trees. The expression tree interpreter (`preferInterpretation: true`) throws because it can't handle the ref-struct-based method.\n\n## How to Fix\n\nEither **cast the array** to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the LINQ overload, or **call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly**:\n\n```csharp\n// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n\n// Option 2: Call Enumerable.Contains directly (no extension-method syntax)\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nBoth approaches pin overload resolution to the `IEnumerable<T>`-based `Enumerable.Contains`, which expression trees fully support.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"61c4725e-7335-4e0e-bea4-915d9e5fc165","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on arrays. Let me think about what changed.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension members. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), and as part of this, the compiler's overload resolution for extension methods changed.\n\nBut more specifically, the issue here is about how the compiler resolves `array.Contains(num)` when `array` is `int[]`.\n\nIn .NET 9 and earlier, `int[].Contains()` resolved to `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)` — a LINQ extension method. \n\nThis works fine in expression trees because it's a static method call. But in .NET 10, arrays now implement `IReadOnlyList<T>` directly, which means the compiler might be resolving `Contains()` to a different method — possibly an instance method on `IReadOnlyList<T>` instead of the `Enumerable` extension method. That would break expression trees since instance methods on interfaces can't be directly represented in expression tree syntax the same way. So the real issue is that `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` are ref structs, which expression trees can't handle—they fail at runtime when the compiler tries to interpret an expression tree containing a span-based method call, even though the C# code itself compiles fine. I think the real issue is about overload resolution changes in C# 14/.NET 10, where implicit conversions from arrays to `ReadOnlySpan<T>` are now weighted more heavily. This means the compiler would prefer `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` over `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)` for array arguments, but since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct that can't be used in expression trees, this breaks the lambda expression.\n\nBut wait—the user says this throws at runtime, not compile time. Let me reconsider what's actually happening here. Maybe the C# 14 compiler still resolves to `Enumerable.Contains` for expression trees since it knows span methods can't be included, but something else changed in how the expression tree interpreter or compilation process works in .NET 10. The key insight is that in C# 14, the compiler might be resolving `array.Contains(num)` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` even within expression tree contexts, which could create an expression tree referencing a method that isn't directly serializable or compatible with the expression tree API, causing a runtime failure rather than a compile-time error. The compiler wou